definition.value: Any purine ribonucleoside that is a derivative of xanthosine.

Siloxanes are saturated silicon-oxygen hydrides with unbranched or branched chains of alternating silicon and oxygen atoms (each silicon atom is separated from its nearest silicon neighbours by single oxygen atoms). By extension hydrocarbyl derivatives are commonly included.
Saturated silicon-oxygen hydrides with unbranched chains of alternating silicon and oxygen atoms with general structure H3Si[OSiH2]nOSiH3.
A member of the class of  imidazoles and  thiophenes  that is an angiotensin II receptor antagonist used for the treatment of high blood pressure.
Macromolecular or oligomeric derivatives of siloxanes, usually considered unbranched, of general formula [-OSiR2-]n (R =/= H).
Compounds having rings of alternating silicon and oxygen atoms.
A siloxane where Si is substituted with organyl groups.
An erythrose phosphate that is D-erythrose carrying a phosphate group at position 4. It is an intermediate in the pentose phosphate pathway and Calvin cycle.
An ergoline alkaloid comprising ergoline lacking hydrogens at positions 9 and 10 and also having a methyl group attached to the piperidine nitrogen.
Ergotaman bearing a hydroxy group at the 12' position, isopropyl groups at the 2' and 5'alpha positions, and oxo groups at positions 3', 6', and 18. It is a natural ergot alkaloid.
A pyranonaphthoquinone antibiotic from strain OS-3966 of Streptomyces rosa var. notoensis.
An aflatoxin having a hexahydrocyclopenta[c]furo[3',2':4,5]furo[2,3-h]chromene skeleton with oxygen functionality at positions 1, 4 and 11.
Ergotaman bearing benzyl, hydroxy, and isopropyl groups at the 5', 12' and 2' positions, respectively, and oxo groups at positions 3', 6', and 18. It is a natural ergot alkaloid.
A phenol having the structure of m-cresol substituted at the 6-position with an amyl group.

A substance used locally on humans and other animals to destroy harmful microorganisms or to inhibit their activity (cf. disinfectants, which destroy microorganisms found on non-living objects, and antibiotics, which can be transported through the lymphatic system to destroy bacteria within the body).
